<TEXT>
ending years of strict protectionism the 
government today radically liberalized foreign investment 
regulations in a bid to attract capital to mexicos debtcrippled 
economy 
the new rules announced monday open to foreign investment 
sectors of the economy previously closed to outsiders and increase 
the amount of foreign ownership permitted in others 
in some key areas such as tourism mexico will allow 100 
percent foreign ownership a 1973 law had limited foreign ownership 
to 49 percent in most industries and prohibited it altogether from 
many others 
the new regulations take effect a day before negotiations on 
restructing mexicos 1074 billion foreign debt resume in new 
york mexicos pledge to move away from a protectionist economy is 
a crucial feature of the debt talks 
for technology modernization employment fresh resources and 
access to external markets there is a clear justification and 
rationale to permit increased flexibility to foreign investment in 
mexico commerce secretary jaime serra puche told a news 
conference monday 
many industries considered strategic including banking 
petroleum mineral exploration electrical generation and 
broadcasting will remain offlimits to foreigners he said 
the government is opening previously closed areas such as auto 
parts telecommunications fishing and petrochemicals production a 
maximum of 49 percent foreign investment will be allowed in these 
areas 
areas previously limited to 49 percent foreign ownership that 
will be expanded to make foreign majority ownership possible 
include glass cement iron steel and cellulose 
no country can modernize without attracting fresh 
investment serra puche said the tendency in the world is 
moving toward interdependence 
the new regulations follow other economic reforms including a 
wageandprice control program that cut inflation from a record 159 
percent in 1987 to 517 percent last year 
under president carlos salinas de gortari the government also 
has sold or closed some stateowned industries 
tourism mexicos secondlargest earner of foreign exchange had 
been limited to 49 percent foreign ownership now 100 percent 
foreign ownership will be allowed 
serra puche said that in contrast to the old the new 
regulations will simplify and clarify investment procedures he 
said approval for 100 percent outside ownership will be automatic 
in many cases 
there has been nearly no growth in the mexican economy because 
of the nations foreign debt and low oil prices 
mexican officials say foreign capital is essential to creating 
jobs importing high technology and stimulating exports and 
productivity the commerce department said foreign investment 
totalled 31 billion last year 
the new rules will consolidate regulations pertaining to the 
border maquiladora industry serra puche said but not change 
them 
under the maquiladora program foreignmade parts are imported 
dutyfree to mexico for final assembly when the finished product 
is exported to the united states the united states taxes only the 
labor or the value added in mexico 
speculation that foreign investment restrictions would be eased 
was sparked recently when tourism secretary carlos hank gonzalez 
returned from a visit to europe and announced several resort hotel 
projects involving spanish and west german firms 
much of mexicos tourism is along its coasts and the new rules 
will double the length of beachfront property leases from 30 years 
to 60 years serra puche said the constitution prohibits outright 
foreign ownership of coastal real estate 
