americans are softening their view of the soviet 
union as a military threat but half still believe moscow seeks 
world domination according to a poll published today 
the new york timescbs news poll found that the number of people 
who believe the soviet threat is constantly growing and presents 
a real immediate danger to the united states dropped to 26 
percent from 64 percent in 1983 two years before mikhail s 
gorbachev took power 
in addition the number who think gorbachev is a radical 
departure from his predecessors grew from 47 percent in his first 
year to 65 percent in 1987 and 79 percent now 
however the poll said 50 percent believe the soviet union seeks 
world domination and 57 percent said moscow would start a war to 
get something it wanted 
the poll also found americans are less interested in china than 
in the soviet union and generally believe the chinese are less 
aggressive than the soviets 
of the 1073 people questioned 30 percent had favorable 
opinions toward the soviet union 24 percent had unfavorable 
opinions and 43 percent were neutral the poll said that represents 
a doubling of positive sentiment toward the soviet union since 1987 
the poll taken from may 9 to may 11 also found twothirds like 
the soviet unions proposal to negotiate about the elimination of 
shortrange nuclear missiles in europe 
