<TEXT>
housing construction feeling the bite of 
higher interest rates fell 27 percent in april to the lowest 
level in more than six years the government said today 
it marked the first time housing construction had dropped for 
three straight months since the pace of activity slowed for five 
months in a row from february through june 1987 the commerce 
department reported 
last months decline followed decreases of 45 percent in march 
and 127 percent in february 
new homes and apartments were built at a seasonally adjusted 
annual rate of 136 million units in april the slowest pace since 
the 130 million pace of december 1982 
the housing industry has been among the sectors of the economy 
hardest hit as interest rates have edged upward over the past year 
interest on fixedrate mortgages last month was averaging over 11 
percent up a full percentage point from a year earlier according 
to a national survey by the federal home loan mortgage corp 
the federal reserve board for a year has been pushing up 
interest rates rates in an effort to restrain inflation by 
restraining economic growth 
construction of singlefamily homes rose 51 percent in april to 
an annual rate of 104 million units after dropping 42 percent in 
march and 142 percent in february 
apartment construction meanwhile continued its decline 
falling 213 percent last month to an annual rate of 325000 units 
construction of multifamily units had fallen 53 percent in march 
and 9 percent in february 
the overall decline in housing construction last month was led 
by 108 percent decrease in activity in the west where starts fell 
to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 347000 units 
declines also were recorded in the midwest and south 
construction was down 95 percent in the midwest to a annual rate 
of 277000 units and off 4 percent in the south to a rate of 
529000 
the northeast meanwhile recorded a 359 percent surge in 
construction to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 208000 units 
applications for building permits a barometer of future housing 
activity turned up 72 percent in april after dropping in the 
three previous months 
