<TEXT>
employers who project worker absenteeism 
through race gender or age comparisons are making invalid 
assumptions as well as discriminating a researcher said tuesday in 
releasing a study that said employees who smoke or drink dont miss 
work more than those who dont 
while simple comparisons of the absentee rates of men and women 
for example would show women miss work slightly more than men a 
variety of other variables make such information useless to an 
employer trying to determine if a given job applicant is likely to 
have a poor attendance record said the study by the national 
chamber foundation the research arm of the us chamber of 
commerce 
simply because an individual is a member of a group women 
minorities consumers of alcohol consumers of tobacco simply 
because you can look at the average incidence of absence among 
those groups tells you nothing about the particular behavior of 
individuals in those groups study director carlos e bonilla 
said 
even when a number of variables about a job applicant are 
considered the foundation said there is still no statistically 
supportable formula that would allow employers to identify 
applicants who pose a risk of high absenteeism 
instead employers should rely on their subjective opinion of 
applicants and if possible conduct thorough background checks 
including references from former employers the latter task has 
become increasingly difficult in recent years because employers are 
hesitant to provide adverse information about former workers out of 
a fear of lawsuits even if the information conveyed is accurate 
while smoking and drinking cannot be statistically associated 
with absenteeism physical activity did prove to be a significant 
factor the study said 
more physically fit individuals experience fewer work 
absenteeism and employer initiatives that increase the level of 
physical activity among the work force may indeed have a positive 
effect on employee absenteeism it said 
the foundation based its results on 33000 responses to surveys 
conducted in 1983 and 1985 by the federal governments national 
center for health statistics all of the respondents included in 
the study were 18 years of age or older and had jobs 
the study was released a week after the center using some of 
the same data released a study of its own saying sickness keeps 
women away from work about one day more a year than men while the 
authors of that report gave no reason for their finding a 1985 
labor department study said women have higher rates of absenteeism 
in their childbearing years 
the foundation did not dispute those findings saying that when 
gender was the only variable in determining absenteeism women were 
more likely to miss work than men 
in other singlevariable comparisons the study found the 
probability of work loss 
dropped with increases in age 
dropped as education levels rose 
was higher among married workers 
was lower among nonwhites 
was lower as family income increased 
bonilla said those variables were chosen because such 
information is readily available to employers when considering job 
applicants but no variable by itself can provide anything more 
than a generalization about a given group and that generalization 
cannot be projected to an individual applicant he said 
the conventional wisdom based on broad aggregations of 
individuals is inappropriate for use in evaluating the work loss 
behavior of a particular applicant the report said 
even if all of an individuals traits were combined no 
clearcut trends relating to absenteeism develop bonilla said 
in reality groups defy objective comparison bonilla said 
of three lifestyle characteristics examined by the study 
smoking drinking and physical activity only physical activity 
was found to have a statistically significant impact on work 
attendance 
the chamber group said employers who took an applicants race 
gender or age into account when trying to determine likely work 
attendance a key variable in profitability not only would be 
violating antidiscrimination laws but also would be using a faulty 
theory that may very well deprive the employer of well qualified 
employees 
</TEXT>
