<TEXT>
a gallup survey released tuesday found most 
south africans oppose international economic sanctions saying such 
measures would lead to more joblessness in their nation 
only one in six blacks said sanctions are a good idea because 
they would force the government to abolish apartheid six of 10 
blacks said they would oppose sanctions even if these led the 
government to resign within five years 
the survey of 2192 people 1400 blacks 392 whites and 400 of 
mixed race and asian origin was commissioned by the south african 
chamber of mines representing the countrys mining industry 
of those polled 82 percent of the blacks and 95 percent of the 
whites rejected foreign sanctions with most saying they would lead 
to higher unemployment 
release of the survey coincided with a visit set this week by 
leaders of south africas prosanctions movement including nobel 
prizewinning archbishop desmond tutu seeking support from 
president bush and congressional leaders for proposed negotiations 
between the black majority and the white south african government 
to end racial segregation policies 
tom main chief executive of the mining association said the 
study was commissioned to provide a definitive idea of the pros 
and cons in the sanctions debate as other countries consider 
whether to follow the us example and impose trade restrictions on 
south africa 
congress imposed limited sanctions on south africa in 1986 
overriding a veto by thenpresident reagan in an effort to force 
the government to grant political rights to the black majority 
main speaking by satellite from johannesburg said at a news 
conference to present the gallup survey that south africas coal 
mining industry had a drop in 1987 exports from 44 million tons to 
37 million but bounced back last year to post its second best 
exports ever 
the sanctions resulted in the loss of 8000 to 10000 jobs he 
added all of them held by blacks 
the survey conducted between march 11 and may 8 had a 4 
percent margin of error neil upmeyer research director for 
gallup said that to ensure credibility of the responses 
interviews were conducted away from the work place by interviewers 
of the same race as the respondent 
in the survey 59 percent of the blacks and 51 percent of the 
whites 58 percent of all respondents said american companies in 
south africa can help make the government moderate its racial 
policies 
of those polled 77 percent of blacks and 50 percent of whites 
said ending american business operations would seriously hurt the 
south african economy 
