<TEXT>
the vatican on tuesday urged authorities 
worldwide to pass tough new laws and enforce existing ones to halt 
what it says is an alarming rise in pornography and violence in the 
media it supported boycotting sponsors of offending programs 
the right to freedom of expression does not exist in a 
vacuum it said in a 13page document issued after a fiveyear 
study by the pontifical council for social communications 
the document titled pornography and violence in the 
communications media a pastoral response holds that the media 
have become a vehicle for a warped outlook on life the family 
religion and morality 
the legitimate rights to free expression and free exchange of 
information must be respected but so must the rights of 
individuals families and society to privacy public decency and 
the protection of basic values it said 
sound laws must be enacted where they are lacking weak laws 
must be strengthened and existing laws must be enforced 
the document cited no specific cases and named no countries 
the council president american archbishop john p foley and 
secretary italian monsignor pierfranco pastore also declined at a 
news conference to identify specific films programs or 
publications considered pornographic or identify particular 
countries 
but foley criticized films such as some kung fu movies that 
depict violence for the sake of violence and scenes where 
individuals appear to enjoy inflicting physical harm on others 
that is a type of violence that is really disgusting and can 
give individuals terrible ideas to act out he said 
some soap operas and other tv offerings in latin america are 
becoming more and more explicit and some in the united states are 
suggestive he said 
these dramatic programs can certainly reflect moral evil 
that is part of reality but they shouldnt glamorize evil and make 
evil something which is to be desired he said 
the document condemned pornography as a violation of human 
dignity and rights and of christian values it said the media 
lured by profits tragically succumbed to the temptation of 
exploiting human weakness 
pornography and sadistic violence debase sexuality corrode 
human relationships exploit individuals undermine marriage and 
family life foster antisocial behavior and weaken the moral fiber 
of society itself it said 
even softcore pornography can have a progressively 
desensitizing affect gradually rendering individuals morally numb 
and personally insensitive to the rights and dignity of others 
exposure to pornography can also be like exposure to 
narcotics habit forming and can lead individuals to seek 
increasingly hardcore and perverse material 
foley said the church wants to express solidarity with families 
and particularly with women who he said feel themselves to be the 
special victims of pornography and violence in the media 
he said the church supports groups such as those in the united 
states that organized boycotts of sponsors of programs they 
consider offensive 
it is their right to do so and if they feel certain things 
are damaging to their children perhaps it is even their duty to do 
so he said 
foley said the media should police themselves through 
professional codes that the church needs to maintain a clear and 
constant teaching of the faith and that parents should provide 
children with healthy attitudes toward sexuality and a basic sex 
education 
a fundamental reason for the spread of pornography or violence 
in the media would seem to be a pervasive moral permissiveness 
rooted in the search for personal gratification at any cost the 
council said 
the more sexual activity is considered as a continuing 
frenzied search for personal gratification rather than as an 
expression of enduring love and marriage the more pornography can 
be considered as a factor contributing to the undermining of 
wholesome family life 
the council said willing participation in producing or 
disseminating pornography can only be judged as a serious moral 
evil 
</TEXT>
