<TEXT>
us supreme court justice anthony m 
kennedy on tuesday blocked a 15yearold girl from obtaining an 
abortion without the consent of her parents or a judge 
in effect kennedy reinstated a 1988 state law that had been 
struck down as unconstitutional by a florida appeals court 
his ruling means a minor seeking an abortion in florida will 
still have to get permission from her parents or a judge until at 
least thursday when the full us supreme court reviews kennedys 
decision at a conference 
kennedy acted without comment after the florida supreme court 
earlier in the day decided to allow the girl and all other minors 
in florida to obtain abortions without adult consent until the 
florida justices hear arguments on the matter in september 
kennedys action will stand only until the full court considers 
it the justices could continue to keep the law in effect until 
they decide whatever constitutional issues may be involved 
another option would be to lift kennedys stay and let the 
decision of the 5th district court of appeal in daytona beach stand 
until the federal justices or the state supreme court rule on the 
merits 
i think we are examining a law that needs to be examined that 
needs to be very clear for the trial courts said jerri blair 
the girls lawyer before kennedy ruled ultimately what will 
happen it will cause the legislature to revisit and clarify the 
guidelines 
fourteen states including florida have consent laws but two 
are unenforced and three have been blocked by courts said kathryn 
kolbert an american civil liberties union lawyer in new york city 
in 12 other states ms kolbert said parents only have to be 
notified about the abortion but that is not enforced in four 
states and courts have blocked the laws in five other states 
in february the us supreme court allowed kentucky to begin 
enforcing a 1986 parental notification law the justices without 
comment turned down an emergency request by abortionrights 
activists seeking to block the law 
this time the request for an emergency stay was filed by a 
lawyer appointed to represent the interest of the fetus 
certainly time is of the essence and that can be determined 
from the flurry of activity said attorney richard boylston of 
tavares 
the girl is 12 weeks pregnant and many clinics wont perform 
abortions after the 13th week because of a greater risk of medical 
complications ms blair said 
its our view that its highly inappropriate that a lawyer 
should be appointed for the fetus said ms kolbert she said the 
aclu which filed a friendofthe court brief with the state 
supreme court may do the same in the nations high court 
the national organization for women issued a statement in 
washington that read in part every passing day has the potential 
of making an abortion more difficult and possibly dangerous if not 
impossible for the young woman whose life has become a judicial 
football 
those following the case said kennedys action caught them by 
surprise and they could not immediately analyze what it might mean 
to abortionconsent laws around the nation 
i have no idea whatsoever what is going on said charlene 
carres counsel for floridas branch of the american civil 
liberties union 
others noted that the final disposition of such state laws as 
floridas would have to await results of a us supreme court 
review of a missouri case in which it could revise the roe vs wade 
decision that legalized abortion in 1973 
state rep daniel webster a republican who sponsored the 
abortion consent law last year called the state courts ruling 
striking down the abortion consent law only temporary and said 
were looking at a broader picture 
the florida law requires unmarried girls under 18 to obtain the 
consent of their parents or a judge 
in the case in which kennedy acted a girl petitioned a court 
may 2 for permission to get an abortion she said she could not 
approach her parents without fear of emotional or physical abuse 
two days later circuit judge jerry t lockett denied the 
petition saying the law was unworkable because it is 
unconstitutionally vague and does not let judges hold proper 
hearings the case then went to the appeals court which struck 
down the law 
of approximately 75000 abortions performed in florida last 
year about a third were on minors according to abortionrights 
activists 
since the law took effect in february few teenagers have gone 
through the courts to seek a judges permission for an abortion 
janis comptoncarr executive director of the florida abortion 
rights action league said many youngsters are going to georgia to 
get abortions 
the now statement noted kennedy the high courts newest member 
has not yet ruled on an abortion case but his decision to block the 
florida ruling bears out the groups suspicion that he is hostile 
to the constitutional concept oulthood 
shapiro who has worked on the virus strain for about seven 
years at the agencys insect pathology laboratory in beltsville 
md named the new virus abby after the town where it was found 
abington mass 
the abby virus showed up early in the studies as one of the most 
effective of 19 different strains of nuclear polyhdrosis virus or 
npv around the world the npv strains infect gypsy caterpillars 
but may not always prevent them from defoliating trees 
but shapiro said the abby virus demonstrated in laboratory tests 
that it can kill more caterpillars 10 times faster than the 
standard npv which has been used for two years by the national 
park service in selected areas of rock creek park in washington 
dc 
park officials said that wherever npv was sprayed there was 
little or no defoliation to the trees shapiro said and that 
was the natural strain not abby 
gypsy moths in the caterpillar or larvae stage are voracious 
eaters of foliage they have gradually spread from massachusetts 
where they were imported in 1969 by a french biologist to breed 
with native american silkworms 
but the moths escaped from the laboratory and started eating 
foliage the scientist louis trouvellot returned to france and 
pursued a career in astronomy 
