<TEXT>
the rail line wrecked by a runaway 
train that leveled homes killing four people reopened tuesday 
after southern pacific and the city reached an agreement heading 
off a threatened court order 
the first train down the cajon pass rolled past the site of the 
accident at 405 pm and the second train followed 40 minutes 
later said southern pacific spokesman jerry pera 
city attorney james penman with city council authorization to 
seek an injunction keeping the track closed insisted on an 
agreement requiring that the railroad buy 11 properties damaged in 
the accident friday 
southern pacific had agreed to buy seven 70000 homes that were 
demolished and agreed tuesday afternoon to buy the other four and 
accepted the citys demand for an undeveloped land buffer in case 
of another derailment 
southern pacific also agreed to pay the costs of relocating 
residents and housing them for 90 days pick up the citys cleanup 
costs and defend san bernardino in any lawsuit resulting from the 
wreck 
penman said the agreement prevented a potentially protracted 
court fight we know it is difficult to get an injunction against 
a national transportation arm he said 
eight trains that normally use the line daily had been rerouted 
since friday when a train traveling 90 mph jumped the tracks on a 
curve trains are supposed to take at 30 mph two boys in a home and 
two crewmen were killed 
penman said the railroad complained that it is losing 1 million 
a day while the track is closed 
the national transportation safety board was winding down 
interviews tuesday in a monday night briefing officials said 
trainman larry hill didnt tell the lead engineer about a set of 
failed brakes on the train 
hill also told investigators that he failed to activate 
emergency brakes for 13 miles after first noticing a loss of 
pressure in brake lines officials said 
ntsb officials said there also was a chance the crew of the 
69car southern pacific freight train was unaware of how heavy 
their freight was and miscalculated the braking needed down the 
pass where the accident occurred 
