<TEXT>
polands election campaign is under way with 
opposition candidates in the running an associated press 
correspondent went out into the countryside recently to watch poles 
experiencing something new in their lives this is his report 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
in the lazy afternoon sun the people of 
this vacation area close by the soviet border gathered around a 
park bandshell where a union troubadour strummed a guitar 
men in white golfing hats emblazoned with the red solidarity 
logo handed out paper flags to children while at folding tables 
volunteers sold campaign bricks coupons printed to look like 
bricks to build a campaign fund 
in a scene similar to the fourth of july in smalltown america 
solidarity was going to the people in polands experiment with a 
new political style democracy 
historian bronislaw geremek and filmmaker andrzej wajda were 
kicking off their campaigns for the national assembly in warsaw on 
the ticket of the solidarity citizens committee 
a deal between the solidarityled opposition and communist 
authorities lets the opposition seek 161 seats in the existing 
460seat sejm and creates a 100member senate the east blocs 
first fully democratic legislative chamber 
solidarity has 261 candidates campaigning in all of the 
countrys 49 provinces 
their bustling election offices are provided by authorities and 
staffed by volunteers while leaflets placards and flags are paid 
for from small campaign donations collected at tables set up by the 
local citizens committees officials say the money comes in too 
quickly to count 
some communist candidates also have been out meeting voters but 
in general theyve been slower to take up the westernstyle 
campaigning 
despite occasional murmurs about carpetbaggers from warsaw 
wajda last lived in suwalki when he was 7 years old and geremek 
never lived here this town of 59000 people was puffed up to have 
two such renowned candidates and gave them a warm reception even 
the communist mayor received them 
wajda is polands bestknown filmmaker geremek one of lech 
walesas closest advisers is an architect of the roundtable 
talks that ended april 5 making solidarity legal again and opening 
the way to the june 4 vote 
joining them were the local members of the solidarity slate 
jerzy pietkiewicz a 41yearold teacher from nearby elk and 
stanislaw bernatowicz an elderly scientist active in protecting 
the regions lakes and forests 
wajda and bernatowicz running for senate and geremek and 
pietkiewicz for the sejm sounded similar themes at the park rally 
with about 1000 townspeople poland needs independence the system 
has failed and voters should use the elections to end the power 
monopoly held by the communist party officially the polish united 
workers party 
at first slow and nervous the intense pietkiewicz soon was 
being interrupted by cheers 
do we really live in a polish state he asked if those 
who have ruled have had to go to red square for instructions 
he said poland was victimized by a marxistleninist philosophy 
that wrongly thought it could create paradise of earth through 
materialistic values that ignored religion and truth 
said geremek it cannot be any longer as it is now 
everyday suffering lines lack of money or lack of goods hard 
life for women lack of hope and lack of prospects for youth 
it has to be changed 
candidates stressed the elections are a step to totally free 
voting in four years authorities promised as much at the round 
table but the opposition is skeptical making solidarity a 
parliament force is seen as a way to hold the communists to their 
word or as one pamphlet put it each vote for our candidates is 
a step toward freedom 
