all cigarette packets sold in the 
european economic community will have to carry specific health 
warnings from jan 1 1993 the eec decided tuesday 
in addition they will have to carry a general warning that 
tobacco seriously damages health which will also have to be 
carried by products such as pipe tobacco 
smoking causes cancer smoking causes fatal diseases 
pregnant women smoking harms your baby and smokers die 
younger are some of the specific warnings which will have to 
appear on cigarette packs 
ministers from the 12 eec member states also agreed at a meeting 
on tuesday that the warnings should be clear and legible printed 
in bold letters and should not be printed on external wrappers or 
where they would be damaged when the package is opened 
the new law specified that the warning must cover at least 4 
percent of the packet in countries where there is one official 
language if there are two official languages 6 percent of the 
surface must be covered and where there are three official 
languages 8 percent must be covered 
tar and nicotine levels must also be clearly indicated on 
cigarette packs and must take up the same surface as the health 
warning 
britain although bound by the majority decision was the only 
eec member state to vote against the new law saying that it went 
beyond the eecs powers to adopt legislation to complete the 
internal market by the end of 1992 
by this date all barriers to the free movement of goods 
capital people and services between the 12nation trade bloc 
should be dismantled 
but the eec commission argued that all tobacco products must be 
labeled in the same way otherwise countries could refuse their 
entry on the grounds that they were incorrectly labeled 
the world health organization estimates that 440000 eec 
citizens die every year from diseases caused by smoking 
