<TEXT>
thinking machines corp a small supercomputer 
rival of cray research inc announced two new models on tuesday 
and said it had reached a marketing agreement with digital 
equipment corp 
the cambridge massbased company used a new york news 
conference to describe progress in getting its computers placed 
with industrial and academic customers who use it for complex 
problems such as aircraft design stress analysis and molecular 
biology 
danny hillis thinking machines founding scientist said in an 
interview that his company is the world leader in a style of 
computing known as parallel processing a field in which 
researchers say americans are far ahead of the japanese 
japans nec corp hitachi ltd and fujitsu ltd are chipping 
away at crays lead in supercomputer market share because they are 
better at building fast single processors that dont rely on 
parallel design 
the thinking machines are known as massively parallel computers 
because they harness thousands of relatively lowpowered processors 
to work on a single problem 
the company devotes 80 percent of its effort to the software 
that permits parallel processing to occur hillis said 
i dont subscribe to the view that the japanese are inherently 
no good at software he said but he added i think its a fair 
fight and were ahead 
the thinking machines supercomputers are distinctive for their 
shape large black cubes and the panels of blinking red lights 
visible through a dusky window on one side crays machines are 
shaped like horseshoes 
under the marketing agreement announced tuesday thinking 
machines and digital will market supercomputing systems made up of 
computers from both companies selling them at discounts to as many 
as 25 universities thinking machines said 
the smaller of the two new systems the cm2a comes with either 
4096 or 8192 processors it can perform 1 billion or 2 billion 
operations a second depending on its size and costs 500000 or 
1 million 
the cm2as relatively low price makes it suited for academic 
customers that have previously not been able to afford a 
supercomputer thinking machines said first deliveries are 
scheduled for june 1989 
the more powerful system is an upgrade of the older 
64000processor cm2 it has the same number of processors but 
more internal memory prices range from 2 million to 10 million 
and first deliveries are scheduled for june 1989 
</TEXT>
