<TEXT>
as the season to spray washington state 
apple trees with alar arrives uniroyal chemical co confirmed 
tuesday that none of the controversial chemical has been purchased 
by farmers since january 
the middlebury conn company also disputed studies showing 
that over 30 percent of the nations apples contain alar a growth 
retardant that has been identified as a possible carcinogen in 
recent months 
if all 112000 pounds of alar sold to apple farmers in 1988 had 
been used at 3 pounds per acre it would have covered 76 percent 
of the nations 490000 acres of orchards said christopher exton 
a marketing manager for uniroyal 
the percentage should be even less for the 1989 crop 
sales have been zero from the beginning of february exton 
said in a telephone interview noting that demands by some 
politicians and consumer groups to remove alar from the market 
would accomplish little since none is being sold 
battered by low sales and slumping prices the apple industry is 
voluntarily backing off on alar use in an attempt to win back 
consumer confidence 
the growth regulator is sprayed on trees during the spring and 
summer and improves the color crispness and shelf life of red 
apples 
i know of no one who is planning on using it said chris 
schlect head of the northwest horticultural council in yakima i 
would be very much surprised in anybody intends to use it this 
spring 
washington produces half the nations apples and many growers 
have joined the call for an alar ban as a way to win back their 
markets 
a debate has arisen over exactly how much alar is used with the 
federal government and the industry initially contending it was 
about 5 percent and last week revising the figure to up to 15 
percent 
the cbs program 60 minutes on sunday said some studies 
indicated up to 38 percent of the crop is treated 
but exton said studies showing a high use of alar are 
statistically flawed 
alar is used to improve shelf life of stored apples so the 
number of alartreated apples is greater this time of year than 
earlier in the season exton said 
alar the marketing name for daminozide makes up less than 1 
percent of uniroyals 750 million in annual sales and sales have 
declined 75 percent since 1985 when the controversy first came to 
light exton said 
the chemical is also used on peanuts and some cherries and on 
nonedible trees and plants he said 
the controversy began when the private natural resources defense 
council issued a report in late february that concluded that 
consuming apples or apple products treated with alar increased 
cancer risk in children 
</TEXT>
